Title: Kruskal's algorithm in 2 minutes ‚Äî Review and example
Comment: Your basic knowledge of this algorithm is correct however your method is wrong. You do have to start with the shortest length but you have to create a list: CE1, AB2, AC3, AD3, BE3,  BC4. CD5, DF7, EF8, FG9. You then go back through the list and draw each length in turn - CE, AB, AC and AD can all be drawn; BE forms a cycle and so should be discarded. Likewise, BC and CD also form cycles and so should be discarded. DF and FG can both be drawn but FE must too be discarded because it forms a cycle. You can then work out the total length of the minimum spanning tree, which is 25. On the list, you should put a small tick by each length that has been used and a small cross by each length that has been discarded.
